article.description: Shereka Wright scored 13 of her 21 points in the second half Sunday to help rally No. 7 Purdue to a 66-63 victory over Houston.
article.headline: Wright scores 13 in second half to lift Purdue
article.linkText: No. 10 Purdue turns to Wright in rally over Houston
article.story: HOUSTON (AP) -- Shereka Wright delivered important baskets for Purdue -- again. Wright scored 13 of her 21 points in the second half Sunday to help rally No. 7 Purdue to a 66-63 victory over Houston. "We obviously were trying to get the ball in her hands late in the game," Purdue coach Kristy Curry said. "That's what has made her who she is. She seems to deliver whenever we need her to late in games and she did it again this time." Wright played high school basketball at Copperas Cove and had between 30 and 40 family and friends watching her for the first time since she went to Purdue. "It was definitely important for me to come back to Texas and do well," said Wright, who scored nine points in the final 6:31. "It was important for us to get a win, but it also meant a lot for me personally playing in front of my family and friends." Another Texan, Erika Valek of Lubbock, had 10 points and six assists as Purdue (6-1) won its fifth straight. "This was an important game for us to grow and learn from," Valek said. "It was also big for me to come back to Texas. I didn't have as many in the stands as Shereka did. I only had about 15-to-20. But just having them there meant a lot to me." Chandi Jones scored 24 points and Sancho Lyttle 23 for Houston, which lost its second straight after winning its first five games. The Cougars also lost to No. 9 Georgia on Wednesday. "It's tough to lose to Purdue, but not to lose to Kristi," said Houston coach Joe Curl, who had Curry as an assistant when both were at Stephen F. Austin in 1993-94. "I'm very encouraged by our team. It was disappointing to lose, but there were a lot of very positive aspects of this game for us. "But Wright was tough. She really took the ball to the rim late and we had no answer for her." Jones agreed that the Cougars profited from the loss. "I think we played hard enough to win but it just didn't happen," Jones said. "I'll live with being beaten by Purdue by just three points. I think these last two losses just build us up to go strong the rest of the season." Lindsey Hicks scored four points in a six-point run as Purdue erased a two-point deficit and moved into the lead to stay with 5:35 remaining. Wright added two baskets in the final 1:48 to help seal the win. Purdue charged to an 11-5 lead in the opening 2:28, but Lyttle scored seven points in an 8-2 run that gave Houston a 29-26 lead with 4:06 left in the first half. Lyttle finished with 15 first-half points and Jones had 12 as Houston took a 34-30 lead at the break.
